 font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">General - Concerns of UK / Northern Ireland citizen regarding the banking sector</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">The Banking structure in Northern Ireland</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Purpose of the 2013 Northern Ireland Affairs Committee’s call for evidence on the banking structure in Northern Ireland in connection to the official NI Banking Enquiry   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Four NI Banks collaboration / collusions in reducing operating costs via unethical</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"> means</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Activities relating to the Four NI banks cost saving ‘initatives’</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Nature of collusions to which the ‘big four’ NI banks are complicit</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11.5pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Overview</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">General - Concerns of UK citizen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> regarding the banking sector   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The banking sector in general is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> one which has been a source of concern to many, not least with regards to the unprecedented levels of sharp practice, deceptions and fraudulent behaviours of recent times, much of which has been documented by many, including politicians and media, and re </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">which most, if not all, came to the attention of the UK and Northern Irish public, not through voluntary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> disclosure and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> transparency of the banks, but through the actions of others.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">It is the case that whistleblowing channels advised, or implied, by the b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">anks via disingenuous published Corporate Social Responsibility Statements do not function as it is implied they do, a position which is indicative on one where the offender is also the ‘policing’ body, a position which for obvious reasons does not work.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Many cannot understand why regular laws which apply to the majority have not been seen to apply to those within the banking sector who set the corporate tone to which various deceptions and fraudulent behaviours (including bank officials providing inaccura</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">te information under oath, falsifying of documents, etc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, activities which at one time few would have thought banks would engage in, have prevailed, do not appear to apply to senior banking sector officials and executives, with questions asked by many as t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">o why this may be.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Many UK citizens remain confused as to why ‘ordinary persons’ are subject to stiff punishment for what are often fairly minor misdemeanours, whilst bankers responsible for hugely significant misdemeanours impacting upon every man, wo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">man and child in UK, appear to have got off scot free, usually with huge financial packages of one sort or another intact, hedging those individuals from the negative impacts their behaviours helped to heap upon the majority of the nations citizens.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">There</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> is evidence to suggest that operating principles possibly assumed to apply mainly to corporate tone setting senior banking executives may be more prevalent amongst some bank employees further down the corporate chain, as some employees, mindful of the sta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">te of the economy and equally mindful of their own perceived job securities and future promotion prospects seek to consolidate their own positions via enthusiastic and compliant adherence to dubious operating principles and aims of the organisations which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">employ them.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">There have even been new (and annoying) industries formed on the foundation of banking sector sharp practices, with for instance, millions of people frequently harassed by telephone callers, pre recorded voice messages and SMS text messages</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> relating to PPI, a sector which as stated, would not even exist had it not been for banking sharp practice on which it is founded. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Given the events of the past few years, some feel there is justification for an independent body to be established where a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ll persons or organisations, not just from a customer perspective, but from all backgrounds where direct and negative impact has been encountered as a result of banking sector sharp practices</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and where any party who feels such sharp practices should be ex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">posed, can do so without fear of retribution brought about by any bank or combination of banks, or from any third party or parties engaged by any bank or banks in connection to same.     </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-------------------------------------------------------------</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">The Banking structure in Northern Ireland</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The Northern Ireland Affairs call for evidence into the banking structure in Northern Ireland is welcomed by many (as is the recently announced banking enquiry in the Republic of Ireland (ROI) to be held at futur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e dates, those dates as yet undecided).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The reason why ongoing or pending</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">banking enquiries across the island of Ireland may be considered to be of interest to citizens of Northern Ireland / United Kingdom is because in Northern Ireland (and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to a lesser degree</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> on mainland UK) two of the Irish pillar banks are significant players, those banks being Bank of Ireland and the AIB (Allied Irish Banks) owned First Trust Bank (AIB in UK), whilst the Royal Bank of Scotland owned Ulster Bank is a major</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> player across both jurisdictions of Northern Ireland and ROI .</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Of the 4 four </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">‘big four’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> banks operating in Northern Ireland, one of them, Royal Bank of Scotland / Ulster Bank is 82% owned by the UK Taxpayer / UK Government following a circa £45 billion b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ail out in 2008, whilst following similar bailouts also in 2008 in ROI totalling circa €30billion, Bank of Ireland is partially owned by the ROI Taxpayer / ROI Government and AIB, owner of First Trust Bank in Northern Ireland is moreorless in full ownershi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">p of the ROI Taxpayer / ROI Government.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In Northern Ireland, both ROI  banks, Bank of Ireland and First Trust Bank, are hugely influential in the banking affairs of Northern Ireland, are as Ulster Bank and Danske Bank (Northern Bank) a group of four whi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ch traditionally are recognised as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">‘the big four’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> in Northern Ireland banking, with one of the ROI banks, Bank of Ireland also additionally influential in NI and UK in connection to UK / NI Post Office savers via the fact that the bank is tied in with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Post Office</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">(all NI and UK Post Office account holder statements are, unbeknown to many account holders, actually produced in Dublin, not in UK as many believe to be the case, with Post Office statements produced on Bank of Ireland premises and, in order t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">o acquire a UK postmark on all envelopes bound for NI or UK Post Office account holders,  transported via road each day from Dublin to Belfast in order to acquire a UK postmark for every NI / UK bound envelope, delivered into the main UK Royal Mail postal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">facility for Northern Ireland at Mallusk, Co Antrim), a position which previously, for reasons known to the parties in question, some UK savers, UK taxpayers, UK politicians, relevant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">trade </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">union officials, etc, queried or raised concerns.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Of the four ban</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ks which make up ‘the big four’, in Northern Ireland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> only one bank therefore is actually UK owned, whilst as stated, two are ROI owned and one</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, Danske Bank,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Danish owned.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Thus banking in Northern Ireland is hugely affected, and to a lesser degree re UK, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">by influences from outside of Northern Ireland / UK. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Whilst there may be areas of general collaboration between banks within the UK banking sector, some understandable and acceptable perhaps, some not so i.e. Libor rate manipulations, etc, within the structure of the ‘big four’ banks in Northern Ireland ther</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e appears to be areas and levels of collaboration, or collusion, which may not ordinarily be expected to prevail in any circumstances, but which not only do such collaborations and collusions prevail, connected to the position are elements of sharp and une</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">thical practices, and from which persons in Northern Ireland are victims of the practices referred to and from which the ‘big four’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">NI </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">banks unethically derive financial benefit. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">These practices are referred to below under several sub headings.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-------</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">------------------------------------------------------</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> Purpose of the 2013 Northern Ireland Affairs Committee call for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> on the banking structure in Northern Ireland Banking Enquiry</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The purpose of this enquiry is referred to in official parlia</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">mentary terms of gathering </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">‘evidence on the banking structure in Northern Ireland’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, and referred to in other areas i.e. media sources such as BBC News</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> ‘a far reaching enquiry’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">NI banking practices under scrutiny’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, etc. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">There is no doubt that a number of areas require close attention, some of these areas very much focussed in the minds of the public, and thus unavoidable (which may be why the bank(s) concerned have referred to same within their published submissions to th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e NI Affairs Committee) i.e. the Ulster Bank IT debacles, rural and urban branch closures and the impact this has on those affected, etc.    </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">However, whilst volunteering information in relation to issues which the 4 NI banks are unable to influence the committee in terms of whether those issues are to be discussed or otherwise, there are areas of concern re which it is noted that none of the NI</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> banks have made any reference to but which nevertheless need to be addressed, possibly by a body as influential as the NI Affairs Committee. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Despite implied principles in Corporate &amp; Social Responsibility Statements and in other areas, banks are not kno</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">wn for their ‘openness and transparency’, with the general public becoming aware of most, if not all banking misdemeanours not as stated previously through well meaning and ethically minded disclosure by the banks, but through the efforts of others.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">I sug</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">gest that it is important that the NI Affairs Committee looks not only at those issues which the ‘big four’ NI banks refer to within their submissions to the Committee, the published submissions covering what most observers would have expected from the ban</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ks, but as is the case in investigative procedures, often it is what isn’t voluntarily referenced which requires some element of investigation.      </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-------------------------------------------------------------</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Four NI Banks collaboration / collusions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> in reducing</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> operating costs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> via unethical means</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A major part of the ‘structure’ of the traditional main ‘big four’ Northern Ireland banks (Bank of Ireland, Danske Bank, First Trust Bank and Ulster Bank) in relation to the retail branch and other office</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s networks throughout Northern Ireland is a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">sub structure relating to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">combined </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">operating costs relating to the whole across Northern Ireland networks of the ‘big four’ NI banks, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the purpose of which is to reduce individual / sole bank operating costs in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">relation to same and thus to derive the financial benefit from the collaboration referred to.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">However, it is in this particular area in which the 4 NI banks have not only collectively engaged in highly dubious and unacceptable practices of a nature which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">no ethically operating organisation should ever engage, but in doing so it could be suggested that the circumstances have rendered the UK Taxpayer / UK Government (and the ROI Taxpayer / ROI Government) complicit in those same highly dubious, unethical and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> unacceptable practices. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">There are relationships which have or continue to prevail(ed) which would be considered by many to be ‘inappropriate’ and unacceptable, for reasons re which it must be assumed that the resultant financial benefits to each of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">‘big four’ NI banks were the overriding factor regarding why the relationships prevailed / prevail, but in connection to which, in consideration of a number of relevant factors, further benefits to individuals within ‘big four’ NI  banks cannot be discount</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ed.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Practices referred to run contrary to those principles and standards referred to in a number of UK Government publications, including the most recent and highly relevant September 2013 HM Government published document entitled</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> ‘Good Business - Im</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">plementing the UN Guiding Principles on Business and Human Rights’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">(ref: Cm 8695), in which it is stated that this document, foreworded by The Minister of State for Business Innovation and Skills and The President of the UK Board of Trade, Right Honorable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Dr Vince Cable MP and The Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs, Rightt Honourable William Hague MP, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">‘Presented to Parliament by the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs by Command of Her Majesty (Queen Elizabeth II)’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Of particular</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> interest within this document is section in which reference is made to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">‘the activities of UK State-owned, controlled or supported enterprises’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, a group to which the bailed out and currently circa 82% UK Taxpayer owned RBS, owner of the NI / ROI operating </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Ulster Bank, belongs.    </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Within the banking sector there is no question that highly paid regulators did not regulate and law enforcement and Serious Fraud Office officers failed to enforce and to hold to account, with some of those who failed in their hi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ghly paid roles going on to ever better paid positions within those organisations they failed to regulate or hold to account</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">owever it cannot be overlooked that it was banks which systematically committed frauds and various deceptions, aided and abetted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> possibly by ‘sympathetic’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and / or compliant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">entities from within ‘the system’.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">It would appear that where one, a combination of or all of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">‘big four’ NI banks and RBS have engaged in sharp practice and are challenged in connection to same, it is routine to, where responses are provided, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">in connection to dubious procurement and related ‘processes’, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">to use references such as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">‘robust’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and to ref</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">er also to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> ‘independent audit(s’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">) and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">‘investigation’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">processes, with a consistent lack of evidence that such processes are actually carried out, a position which is followed by a consistent refusal to address any issues to which disingenuous and misleadin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">g information is provided.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">To date the citizens of UK and Northern Ireland, and indeed in a number of jurisdictions around the world, have seen little or no evidence of those within the banking sector who have committed or been complicit to sharp pra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ctices, deceptions, fraud, etc being held to account, with many of those individuals, or the banks they work for, continuing to operate along a very much business as usual basis, such is the lack of concern some appear to have regarding being held accounta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ble for any misdemeanours they may be connected to or complicit in. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-------------------------------------------------------------</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Activities relating to the Four NI banks cost saving ‘initatives’</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; 