t-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Maintenence of relationships many would consider to be inappropriate i.e. where there has been connection to illegal / criminal activities, and a bank or banks have chosen for some reason to take a ‘blind eye approach’ in relation to same, and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the pre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">valence of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> ‘unusual procurement related activities’ in relation to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">such r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">elationship(s)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">There are 4 different levels of types of collusion relating to the 4 NI ‘big four’ banks which have prevailed as follows:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.25pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">General ‘Interbank collusions’ between</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the 4 NI ‘big four’ banks</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.25pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Collusions between individual banks, a number of banks or all 4 banks and third party entities, in relation to tender / procurement related issues </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.25pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Collusions between individual banks, a number of banks or all 4 banks and third</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> party entities, in relation to suppression (gagging) of disclosures relating to procurement related and connected issues </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.25pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Internal sole bank collusions between a number of officials or departments, going up to Chief Executive level, including in relation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to brushing under the carpet details brought to the attention of Chief Executives and others regarding the unethical and unacceptable practices referred to, a position which is difficult to reconcile with actions expected to be executed in connection to t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he sort of sharp practices this communication alludes to as referred to within relevant regulatory body publications</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and reality.  </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.25pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-------------------------------------------------------------</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Overview</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Whilst this communication relates to a specific service sector, it cannot be assumed that the ‘principles’ which apply within </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> specific service sector are not repeated on the same basis in other areas, especially where  there are financial benefits to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">had by either one, several or all of the ‘big four’ NI banks</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">There is evidence that some NI government bodies or individuals from within those bodies may be aware of practices and collusions alluded to within this document, but as in internal NI banki</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ng circles, have may have chosen to take a ‘blind eye / turn the other way’ approach for reasons / agendas unknown, but possibly at best, due to general apathy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and lack of interest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and concern, or at worst, due possibly to personal or other relationships i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">nvolving senior NI banking executives.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The citizens of Northern Ireland and UK (and of other jurisdictions i.e. Republic of Ireland) have the right to being able to avail of banking services provided by a bank or banks connected to which ethics and int</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">egrity are unquestionable, where dubious and misleading practices relating to the implying of same and to general fitness and probity standards are not systematic, where third parties i.e. persons working for or providing services to the banks are not subj</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ected to exploitations, including threats, intimidation, etc, and same re persons who may attempt to expose same and to have the banks acknowledge their complicity, etc.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">From this position it is important, necessary even, that alternative organisations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">i.e. credit unions, other banks, which may operate to levels of integrity and ethics which are higher than those of the traditional Northern Ireland ‘big four’ banks, are able to succeed and progress within the N</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">orthern Ireland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> banking marketplace</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and to o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ffer real and proper choice to banking consumers in Northern Ireland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, a position which may progress partly to the obstacles to moving bank account which prevailed previously having </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">recently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">been removed.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">I suggest that it is also important that, as referr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ed to previously, the NI Affairs Committee seeks to establish some form of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">whistleblowing facility</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> for persons within or connected in any shape or form to the NI banking sector i.e. employee, service provider, employee of a service provider to the NI banki</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ng sector, and not just bank customers, to be able to bring to the attention of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">a relevant body which is completely independent of the banks themselves</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, misdemeanours and activities to which entities from within the NI banking sector may be complicit, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">in connection to which the banks, as has been the case previously and currently, not least as, despite having reference within disingenuous Corporate &amp; Social Responsibility Statements to the availability of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">‘whistleblowing channe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">’ which are in fact ineffective, the banks are no longer able to operate to an agenda designed to ensure that certain issues i.e. relating to sharp practices, are kept under the radar so to speak, and that there is no longer any sort of misplaced reliance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">in some quarters on the ineffective whistleblowing channels of the banks, channels which, as stated, have been shown not to function as most non bank official individuals would expect, and deliberately so in some, possibly most instances.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">There is no q</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">uestion that any form of self policing system within the banking sector, for the purpose of this document within the Northern Ireland banking sector, and particularly in respect of the ‘big four’, Bank of Ireland, Danske Bank, First Trust Bank and Ulster B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ank, does not work, with such an arrangement shown to be open to abuse and self serving manipulations from within the banking sector.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">This is a position which is demonstrated by a significant number of acknowledgements to issues raised and assurances th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">at those issues will be followed up, only for them to be buried or subject to interference from third party entities, and by the range of tactics readily employed by the banks in relation to attacks of various sorts on the likes of whistleblower(s), a posi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">tion which cannot be reconciled with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">‘openness and transparency’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">‘high standards’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the banks refer to in disingenuous published Corporate &amp; Social Responsibility Statements and equally disingenuous annual reports and so called Codes of Practice.    </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">      </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">It is a shameful indictment of the levels of integrity and principles of the Northern Ireland ‘big four’ banks, and especially so perhaps with regards to those executives at the top who lead by example and set the corporate tone of those banks whic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">h have and continue to participate in the sort of practices referred to, and who are aware of the prevalence of those practices, that all of the details declared within this communication to the Northern Ireland Affairs Committee are true and factual.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Ther</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e are examples of senior NI bank executives i.e. at Chief Executive level, both in scenarios connected to their high profile banking sector roles and in other high profile non bank roles, implying certain principles, whilst in other areas allowing activiti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">es to prevail in their organisations and turning a blind eye to same, which cannot in any circumstances be reconciled with those implied principles.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">There are even examples within banking whereby it is bewildering to some, possibly to many, how when the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> backgrounds of some i.e. the connections and activities to which they have been connected, are considered by relevant regulatory bodies to attain ‘fitness and probity’ standards, in otherwords to be considered fit and proper to hold high office within fin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ancially regulated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">organisations such as banks, when ordinary business owners of much more modest enterprises would, in consideration of their backgrounds, be likely to regard those same individuals as wholly unsuitable i.e. to not be fit and proper, to be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> offered a position, any position, within their modest entrrprise.     </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">There are also examples re which it could be suggested the facts cannot easily be reconciled with responsibilities detailed within the general requirements and Fitness and Probity re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">quirements deemed to be necessary in senior bank executives i.e. at Chief Executive level, by the relevant UK (and ROI) regulatory bodies.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">I look forward to providing whatever advice and assistance I am able to provide to the NI Affairs Committee in rela</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">tion to the information provided in this document, and if required, to making available supporting evidential documentations to the Committee.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>